<section class="projects-section" id="projects">
  <div class="container">
    <div class="row">
      <div class="col-lg-12">
        <div class="hr-section">
          <big class="section-header">
              Projects
          </big>
        </div>
          <!-- Project Template
          <div class="col-md-4">
            <h3>TITLE <a href="GITHUB" target="_blank"><div class="btn btn-xs btn-info gh-btn">GitHub</div></a></h3>
              <a href="LINK" target="_blank"><img class="img-responsive project-image" src="IMAGE"></a>
              <p class="text-left">INFO</p>
          </div>
        -->
          <!-- For first row of projects -->
          <div class="row">
            <div class="col-md-4">
              <h3>Flatcasts <a href="https://github.com/thebrianemory/flatcasts" target="_blank"><div class="btn btn-xs btn-info gh-btn">GitHub</div></a></h3>
                <a href="http://www.flatcasts.com" target="_blank"><%= image_tag("port-flatcasts.jpg", class: "img-responsive project-image") %></a>
                <p class="text-left">Flatcasts is my final Project for <a href="http://learn.co/with/thebrianemory" target="_blank">Flatiron School</a>. I set out to solve a need for my fellow students: how to find a lecture on a particular topic. They can search lectures and easily add new ones using only the YouTube URL. This was built with a Rails back-end API and an Angular front-end and deployed to Heroku.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="col-md-4">
              <h3>Travsto <a href="https://github.com/thebrianemory/travsto" target="_blank"><div class="btn btn-xs btn-info gh-btn">GitHub</div></a></h3>
                <a href="https://travsto.herokuapp.com" target="_blank"><%= image_tag("port-travsto.jpg", class: "img-responsive project-image") %></a>
                <p class="text-left">Travsto is an app built for my Rails assessment at <a href="http://learn.co/with/thebrianemory
                ">Flatiron School</a>. It is my first Rails app that was not simply following a tutorial. It was initially entirely built using Rails and deployed to Heroku. I later added a JavaScript front-end as part of my Rails and JavaScript assessment.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="col-md-4">
              <h3>Corneal <a href="https://github.com/thebrianemory/corneal" target="_blank"><div class="btn btn-xs btn-info gh-btn">GitHub</div></a></h3>
                <a href="https://github.com/thebrianemory/corneal" target="_blank"><%= image_tag("port-corneal.jpg", class: "img-responsive project-image") %></a>
                <p class="text-left">While building my Sinatra app, I didn't find anything that had the functionality of <code>rails new app-name</code> that I liked. At the suggestion of one of my instructors, I forked <a href="https://github.com/c7/hazel" target="_blank">Hazel</a> and made my own Ruby gem. This allowed students to easily get their Sinatra projects up and running.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
          <!-- For second row of projects -->
          <div class="row">
            <div class="col-md-4">
              <h3>Cook This Way <a href="https://github.com/thebrianemory/cook-this-way" target="_blank"><div class="btn btn-xs btn-info gh-btn">GitHub</div></a></h3>
                <a href="https://cook-this-way.herokuapp.com/" target="_blank"><%= image_tag("port-cook-this-way.jpg", class: "img-responsive project-image") %></a>
                <p class="text-left">Cook This Way is a recipe site built on Sinatra. I made it for my <a href="http://learn.co/with/thebrianemory
                ">Flatiron School</a> Sinatra Assessment and deployed it to Heroku. It allows a visitor to view and search recipes, sign in with Facebook, add and edit recipes, and make a recipe their own.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="col-md-4">
              <h3>NFL Top Stories Gem <a href="https://github.com/thebrianemory/nfl-top-stories-cli-gem" target="_blank"><div class="btn btn-xs btn-info gh-btn">GitHub</div></a></h3>
              <a href="https://github.com/thebrianemory/nfl-top-stories-cli-gem"><%= image_tag("port-cli-data-gem.jpg", class: "img-responsive project-image") %></a>
              <p class="text-left">My first project for <a href="http://learn.co/with/thebrianemory
              ">Flatiron School</a> was making a CLI data gem. Using Ruby and Nokogiri, I scraped the NFL stories from ESPN, CBS Sports, Fox Sports, NFL.com, and USA Today and displayed them in the command line. It is published on <a href="https://rubygems.org/gems/nfl-top-stories" target="_blank">RubyGems.com</a>.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
      </div>
  </div>
</section>
